## Iteration v004: ALU Operand Isolation (AND-Clamping)

### Simulation (iverilog / vvp)
```
========================================
v004 ALU OPERAND ISOLATION SIMULATION
========================================
[TEST 1] Active Cycles: ADD, SUB, XOR, AND...
[TEST 2] Inactive Cycles (Toggle suppression test)...
[TEST 3] Back to Active Compute...
========================================
v004 ISOLATION RESULTS
========================================
Active cycles:           4
Inactive cycles:         50
Errors (Equivalence):    0
----------------------------------------
Combinational Toggle Count (Adder cloud):
  Baseline ALU toggles: 122
  Isolated ALU toggles: 8
  Toggle Reduction:     93%
========================================
STATUS: PASS
```

### Synthesis (Yosys 0.9)
```
=== alu_wally (Baseline) ===
   Number of cells:                968
     $_AND_                          1
     (other logic)                 967

=== alu_isolated ===
   Number of cells:               1033
     $_AND_                         66
     (other logic)                 967
```

### Comparison: Baseline ALU vs Isolated ALU
| Metric | Baseline ALU | Isolated ALU | Delta |
|--------|--------------|--------------|-------|
| Total cells | 968 | 1033 | +65 (+6.7%) |
| AND gates (`$_AND_`) | 1 | 66 | +65 |
| Adder Cloud Toggles (50 inactive cycles) | 122 | 8 | **-93%** |

**Power impact:** The 65 extra AND gates exactly map to masking the two 32-bit operands (A and B) plus the `SubArith` control signal when `alu_active = 0`. At a tiny 6.7% area overhead, we achieve a massive **93% reduction in switching activity** inside the combinational logic cloud during inactive cycles (e.g. Memory operations, Branches, NOPs).
